1 Regularization

Make simulated data for illustration of regularization method.

  1. Create a function \(Y(X)\) that needs to be minimized and find its minimum.
X<-seq(0,5,length=100)
Y<-.5-1.5*X+.4*X^2
plot(X,Y,type="l")

(act.min<-X[which.min(Y)])
## [1] 1.868687
  1. Add a little noise to the function.
set.seed(9)
Eps<-rnorm(length(X),0,.05)
Y.noise<-Y+Eps
plot(X,Y.noise)

(obs.min<-X[which.min(Y.noise)])
## [1] 2.070707

Even a little noise may change minimum of the observed data.

  1. Apply ideal regularizator to make search for minimum more stable: \[\alpha=0.5-1.5 X +0.4 X^2,\] where function \(\alpha(X)\) is represented by variable regularizator.
regularizator<-.5-1.5*X+.4*X^2

This regularizator is ideal because it âknowsâ the exact function.

Select tuning parameter \(\lambda\) represented by variable tune and minimize function \[Y(X)+\lambda \alpha(X)\] instead of \(Y(X)\).

tune<-.3
matplot(X,cbind(Y.noise,regularizator*tune,Y.noise+regularizator*tune),type="l",lty=1,ylab="Y & Regularizator")

(reg.min.3<-X[which.min(Y.noise+regularizator*.3)])
## [1] 2.070707

Setting tuning parameter to 0.3 did not help finding the real minimum of \(Y(X)\).

Increase the tuning parameter to 1.

tune<-1
matplot(X,cbind(Y.noise,regularizator*tune,Y.noise+regularizator*tune),type="l",lty=1,ylab="Y & Regularizator")

(reg.min.1.0<-X[which.min(Y.noise+regularizator*tune)])
## [1] 2.070707

Still real minimum of \(Y(X)\) is overestimated.

Increase tuning parameter to 3.

tune<-3
matplot(X,cbind(Y.noise,regularizator*tune,Y.noise+regularizator*tune),type="l",lty=1,ylab="Y & Regularizator")

(reg.min.2.0<-X[which.min(Y.noise+regularizator*tune)])
## [1] 1.868687

Now regularization worked: we recovered the actual minimum of the function.

But in real life we do not know ideal regularizator.
What if we set regularizator with a little shift in one of the coefficients?
Consider regularizator \[\alpha(X)= .5-1.5X+.3X^2,\] changing the third coefficient to 0.3 instead of 0.4.

biasedRegularizator<-.5-1.5*X+.3*X^2
matplot(X,cbind(Y,biasedRegularizator),type="l",lty=1,ylab="Y & Regularizator")

matplot(X,cbind(Y.noise,biasedRegularizator*tune,Y.noise+biasedRegularizator*tune),type="l",lty=1,ylab="Y & Regularizator")

(biasedReg.min.2.0<-X[which.min(Y.noise+biasedRegularizator*tune)])
## [1] 2.373737

Lessons:
1. Regularization is a very powerful method that allows using additional information about the solution of the problem.
2. If there is no significant additional information then regularization can be misleading.
3. When applied to regression without additional knowledge about parameters the problem of bias in the parameters and increased variance of their estimators is replaced by the same issues, but in regularizator.

Matrix of determination coefficients shows that there is one significant determination coefficient (>0.5) between predictors: \(\rho^2(ppg45,gleason)=0.573\).

Correlations between predictors make selection of predictors difficult.
For example, predictor lcp is correlated with lcavol, svi and pgg45.
In the presence of all predictors svi is significant with 5% level, but lcp is not.

summary(nolcp.lm)$coefficients[,4]>.05 #no lcp: age, svi,gleason, pgg45
## (Intercept)      lcavol     lweight         age        lbph         svi 
##        TRUE       FALSE       FALSE        TRUE       FALSE        TRUE 
##     gleason       pgg45 
##        TRUE        TRUE

This is a big challenge for any greedy algorithm.

Consider removing all insignificant predictors: age, lcp, gleason and pgg45.

We can test significance of groups of predictors by using F-statistic \[F=\frac{(RSS_0-RSS_1)/(p_1-p_0)}{RSS_1/(N-p_1-1)},\] where \(RSS_1\) is the residual sum of squares of bigger model including all \(p_1+1\) parameters \(\beta_0,\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_{p_1}\); \(RSS_0\) is the residual sum of squares of the model that has only \(p_0+1\) parameters not equal to zero and the rest \(p_1-p_0\) parameters equal to zero: \(\beta_0,\beta_1,\ldots,\beta_{p_0},\beta_{p_0+1}=0,\ldots,\beta_{p_1}=0\).
Such F-statistic measures significance of change in sum of squares of the bigger model if a group of predictors gets eliminated.
Under \(H_0:\beta_{p_0+1}=0,\ldots,\beta_{p_1}=0\) the statistic has F-distribution: \(F \sim F_{p_1-p_0,N-{p_1}-1}\).

significantPredictors.lm<-lm(lpsa~lcavol+lweight+lbph+svi,data=prostateData.norm.train[,-10])

(RSS1<-sum(allPredictors.lm$residuals^2))
## [1] 29.42638
(RSS0<-sum(significantPredictors.lm$residuals^2))
## [1] 32.81499
(statisticF<-(RSS0-RSS1)/(8-4)/RSS1*(67-9))
## [1] 1.669755
1-pf(statisticF,4,67-9)
## [1] 0.1693371

This shows that p-value is large and \(H_0:\beta_{p_0+1}=0,\ldots,\beta_{p_1}=0\) cannot be rejected.

Check assumptions of the model and mean square error of prediction of significantPredictors.lm.

Using both AIC and mean square prediction error as measures of goodness of fit we show that the model with only significant predictors is better than the model with all predictors.

The last MSE value is for the null model.

2.1.3 Lasso regression model

Create a train matrix \(X\) with only inputs and train vector \(Y\) of outputs.

X<-data.matrix(prostateData.norm.train[,1:8])
Y<-prostateData.norm.train[,9]

Fit lasso regression model to train data.

Parameter alpha switches between ridge regression (0) and lasso regression (1).
Argument nlambda is the number of lambda values in the selection process.
Argument lambda.min.ratio is Smallest value for lambda, as a fraction of lambda.max.
No need to standardize because we have done standardization outside.

lassoProstate=glmnet(x=X,y=Y,alpha=1,nlambda=100,lambda.min.ratio=.0001,standardize = F)
names(lassoProstate)
##  [1] "a0"        "beta"      "df"        "dim"       "lambda"    "dev.ratio"
##  [7] "nulldev"   "npasses"   "jerr"      "offset"    "call"      "nobs"
head(cbind(DF=lassoProstate$df,DevRatio=lassoProstate$dev.ratio,Lambda=lassoProstate$lambda))
##      DF   DevRatio    Lambda
## [1,]  0 0.00000000 0.9196376
## [2,]  1 0.09126085 0.8379396
## [3,]  1 0.16702722 0.7634993
## [4,]  1 0.22992978 0.6956721
## [5,]  1 0.28215260 0.6338705
## [6,]  1 0.32550890 0.5775592

Parameter df returned by glmnet() is the number of active predictors at the corresponding level of lambda.
Parameter dev.ratio shows percent of deviance explained.

plot(lassoProstate$lambda,lassoProstate$dev.ratio,type="l",
     ylab="Dev.Ratio",xlab="Lambda")

This plot shows how explained deviance (%) grows as \(\lambda\) becomes smaller.

The following plot shows trajectories of coefficients as \(L_1\)-norm changes, where \(L_1\)-norm is \(|| \mathbf{\beta}||=\sum_i |\beta_i|\).

plot(lassoProstate,col=c("black","red","blue","green","cyan","purple","magenta","gold"),lwd=2)
abline(h=0)
legend("topleft",legend=c("lcavol","lweight","age","lbph","svi","lcp","gleason","pgg45"),
       col=c("black","red","blue","green","cyan","purple","magenta","gold"),lty=1,lwd=2,cex=.7)

The graph shows how coefficients become small and turn into zeros one by one as \(L_1\)-norm decreases.

Next, use cross validation to find the best level of \(\lambda\).

set.seed(15)
cv.out=cv.glmnet(x=X,y=Y,alpha=1)
plot(cv.out)

The plot shows how mean square error changes with \(\lambda\).
Vertical intervals are standard deviation bounds for mean square error.
Left vertical line shows the best parameter \(\lambda\), the vertical line on the right is one standard deviation away.
The best \(\lambda\) is returned by cv.glmnet().

We see that standard errors of each MSE coded by red dots are pretty wide and the difference between \(\lambda_{min}\) and \(\lambda_{min}+\sigma_{\lambda}\) is pretty wide also.
These are the signs that model may not be working very well for this data set.
The lambda minimizing the mean cross-validated error is returned as $lambda.min.

(bestlam =cv.out$lambda.min)
## [1] 0.01109021

Predict the output of the test sample using the model fitted to the train sample and calculate mean square prediction error.

lasso.pred=predict(lassoProstate,s=bestlam,
                   newx=data.matrix(prostateData.norm.test[,1:8]))
(MSE.lasso<-mean((lasso.pred -testOutput)^2)) 
## [1] 0.4969871

Finally, use the best \(\lambda\) to fit the model to the entire sample.

out=glmnet(x=as.matrix(prostateData.norm[,1:8]),y=as.vector(prostateData.norm[,9]),alpha=1,lambda=bestlam,standardize=F)

Find lasso coefficients and compare them with the coefficients of linear model

lasso.coef=predict(lassoProstate,type="coefficients",s=bestlam)
cbind(Lasso=lasso.coef[,1],Lm=as.vector(allPredictors.lm$coefficients))
##                  Lasso          Lm

## lcp         -0.2176740 -0.28849277

As expected, predictor gleason was eliminated.

Compare mean square prediction errors:

2.1.4 PCA

Apply the PCA method to the same data using function princomp().
The final outputs below are obtained using 5 best PCA factors as predictors in linear model.

  • Run PCA
  • Extract factors and loadings
  • Fit linear model using meta-features
  • Apply relimp(), observe the ranks of meta features
  • Reorder factors and loadings according to the ranks
  • Calculate determination coefficients for increasing number of meta features
  • Restore slopes of original features using 5 best meta features in linear model

(Skipped Code)

# run PCA
prostateData.PCA<-princomp(data.matrix(prostateData.norm.train[,1:8]))
summary(prostateData.PCA)

library(relaimpo)
# extract factors and loadings
nFactors<-8
factorLoadings<-prostateData.PCA$loadings[,1:nFactors]
factorScores<-prostateData.PCA$scores[,1:nFactors]
zeroLoading<-prostateData.PCA$center
# fit linear model using meta features
factors8Data<-data.frame(Y=prostateData.norm.train[,9],factorScores)

Calculate MSE for PCR method:

  1. With the test data calculate test meta features using definition of factors in PCR: \[F=X_0~L,\] where
  • \(X_0\) is the test matrix of the original features centered by the zero loading of the PCA model fitted to the train feature matrix
  • \(L\) is the matrix of loadings of the PCA model fitted to the train feature matrix

  1. Reorder test meta features in the order of relative importance of factors of the PCA model fitted to the original features

  2. Predict test response sample with the linear model containing the best 5 train meta features using test meta features as new data

  3. Calculate MSE of the PCR model

3 Using Ridge and Lasso regression with the large number of predictors

3.1 Simulation of the data

In this experiment simulate a series of nested linear models with large number of independent predictors.
The model is: \[Y_{i,j} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i,1} + \ldots + \beta_{i,j} + \epsilon_i;~~i=1,\ldots,500;~~j=2,\ldots,500. \] So, the first model of the series, \(j=2\) is \[Y_{i,2} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i,1} + \beta_2 X_{i,2} + \epsilon_i;~~i=1,\ldots,500.\] And the last model of the series, \(j=500\) is \[Y_{i,500} = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{i,1} + \ldots + \beta_{i,500} + \epsilon_i;~~i=1,\ldots,500.\] All nested models have the same vector of residuals \(\epsilon_i;~~i=1,\ldots,500;\epsilon_i \sim Norm(0,1)\).
All 500 predictors \(X_{i,j};~~j=1,\ldots,500\) are independent samples from \(Norm(0,2).\)
Slopes of the predictors are randomly selected from uniform distribution on \([1,3]\).

set.seed(8394756)
Epsilon<-rnorm(500,0,1)
X<-rnorm(500*500,0,2)
dim(X)<-c(500,500)
colnames(X)<-paste0("X",1:500)
slopesSet<-runif(500,1,3)
Y<-sapply(2:500,function(z) 1+X[,1:z]%*%slopesSet[1:z]+Epsilon)
head(X[,1:5])

Ridge regression did not select predictors. It is expected because we simulated all predictors to be significant.
Ridge regression made a small improvement to mean squared prediction error. This is consistent with expectation because it has one additional parameter.

Regularization is expected to reduce number of predictors when there are collinear (highly correlated) predictors.
Predictors in this example are not collinear.

Lasso removed predictors seemingly randomly regardless of the value of slope.
Given the way the sample was simulated (independent predictors with slopes between 1 and 3) it would be more reasonable removing none or removing the predictors with smallest slopes.

3.6 Large number of predictors, not all of them are significant

To check how lasso regression removes predictors modify the simulated data to make some of predictors insignificant.

set.seed(8394756)
Epsilon<-rnorm(500,0,1)
X<-rnorm(500*500,0,2)
dim(X)<-c(500,500)
colnames(X)<-paste0("X",1:500)
slopesSet<-runif(500,-.1,3)

The previous set was simulated with slopes randomly selected between 1 and 3.
Such selection of slopes made them all distinct from zero which was captured by the linear model.
Now select slopes as random numbers between -0.1 and 3.
Obviously, the slopes which are close to zero should appear as insignificant in a model fit.
